WEBVTT

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:06.320
<v Speaker 1>So now we have a panorama of times in Spanish.

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:08.720
<v Speaker 1>We've seen all of the different times.

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:14.000
<v Speaker 1>We can find will, would, the present, the pasts.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:15.840
<v Speaker 1>The have tenses.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:27.600
<v Speaker 1>Maybe some of these uh we're clearer on than others, but we've learned how to find what we might think we don't know and how to analyze the language so that through listening to Spanish

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:37.300
<v Speaker 1>we can reinforce the language that we've learned and bring it to the surface and pick up again anything that we might have forgotten along the way.

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:41.040
<v Speaker 1>But there is one more tense to learn in Spanish.

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:47.920
<v Speaker 1>One more very important tense in Spanish and personally it's my favorite thing about Spanish.

00:00:47.640 --> 00:01:02.280
<v Speaker 1>In Spanish we have what we can call a mood tense, the subjunctive tense in grammatical terminology, but we will call it the mood tense, because it's a tense that just shows mood.

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:08.720
<v Speaker 1>Now you might be interested to hear that we also have it in English.

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:09.920
<v Speaker 1>Now we don't use it

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:14.120
<v Speaker 1>as much in English as we do in Spanish, but it is there.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:23.000
<v Speaker 1>For example, in English you can say it is important that you are here or it is important that you be here.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:26.320
<v Speaker 1>So it's important that you are here.

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:29.600
<v Speaker 1>Sounds more everyday, let's say, more casual.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:32.000
<v Speaker 1>It's important that you be here.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:33.680
<v Speaker 1>That gives us a different feeling.

00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:35.440
<v Speaker 1>It feels more serious.

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:37.760
<v Speaker 1>It feels more imperative.

00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:39.640
<v Speaker 1>How are we achieving that feeling?

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:42.600
<v Speaker 1>We're using B instead of U R.

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:44.280
<v Speaker 1>We are using U B.

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:46.840
<v Speaker 1>It's important that you be here.

00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:54.940
<v Speaker 1>Another example of how English uses this mood, I might say, had I gone, I would know.

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:56.920
<v Speaker 1>Had I gone, I would know.

00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:03.799
<v Speaker 1>Now had I, that inversion of I had to had I usually is to make a question.

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:06.660
<v Speaker 1>Had you gone already, for example.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:08.100
<v Speaker 1>But here it's not a question.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:10.180
<v Speaker 1>Had I gone, I would know.

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:11.300
<v Speaker 1>Here we are

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:13.079
<v Speaker 1>Creating a mood tense.

00:02:13.079 --> 00:02:17.079
<v Speaker 1>We are saying if I had gone with had I gone.

00:02:17.079 --> 00:02:19.560
<v Speaker 1>We also say not only is it

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:26.040
<v Speaker 1>For example, not only is it a problem, it's the biggest problem.

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:28.840
<v Speaker 1>Not only is it again is it

00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:32.099
<v Speaker 1>is what we do to make a question, but here it's not a question.

00:02:32.099 --> 00:02:34.900
<v Speaker 1>Not only is it a problem, it's the biggest problem.

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:39.060
<v Speaker 1>So the the changing of the order of isn't it

00:02:39.599 --> 00:02:43.760
<v Speaker 1>Gives us this mood tense here in English as well.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:50.959
<v Speaker 1>So we don't need to analyze too much how it works in English because there's not so much correlation between English and Spanish about how it works.

00:02:50.959 --> 00:02:51.599
<v Speaker 1>It's used

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:54.060
<v Speaker 1>much more extensively in Spanish.

00:02:54.060 --> 00:02:57.740
<v Speaker 1>But the idea is not completely alien to us.

00:02:57.740 --> 00:03:01.020
<v Speaker 1>In Spanish it's a very common thing

00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:08.960
<v Speaker 1>That will allow you and oblige you to perceive and to express the world in a certain way

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:18.840
<v Speaker 1>Now to form the mood tense, to form the subjunctive tense in Spanish is very easy and we don't need to learn any new sounds to do it.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:22.540
<v Speaker 1>All we do is we switch between the verbs.

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:27.100
<v Speaker 1>With our verbs we will use the er-ear endings.

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:33.220
<v Speaker 1>And with er ear verbs we will use the R verb endings and that's how we build this tense.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:37.220
<v Speaker 1>So for example, how is to speak?

00:03:38.739 --> 00:03:42.099
<v Speaker 1>And how is he speaks?

00:03:42.099 --> 00:03:42.980
<v Speaker 2>Ablah.

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:43.700
<v Speaker 1>Abla.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:44.500
<v Speaker 2>Sorry, Ablah.

00:03:44.659 --> 00:03:45.379
<v Speaker 1>Abla.

00:03:45.379 --> 00:03:46.099
<v Speaker 1>Abla, good.

00:03:46.099 --> 00:03:47.459
<v Speaker 1>The accent there at the beginning.

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:51.860
<v Speaker 1>Now if you want to make this the mood tense.

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:53.280
<v Speaker 1>We will switch groups.

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:54.640
<v Speaker 1>We will switch groups.

00:03:54.640 --> 00:04:02.480
<v Speaker 1>Verbs from the R group use er-ear endings and verbs from the er-ear group use r endings.

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:05.760
<v Speaker 1>So how would you make abla?

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:07.960
<v Speaker 1>In the mood tense.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:08.840
<v Speaker 2>Able.

00:04:08.840 --> 00:04:09.720
<v Speaker 1>Able.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:10.600
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:13.160
<v Speaker 1>So you have they speak

00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:15.020
<v Speaker 2>Ablan.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:15.820
<v Speaker 1>Ablan.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:19.500
<v Speaker 1>And the mood tense version will be.

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:20.380
<v Speaker 2>Ablan.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:21.180
<v Speaker 1>Ablan.

00:04:21.180 --> 00:04:21.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.420
<v Speaker 1>How is I speak?

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:25.440
<v Speaker 2>Ablo.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:33.200
<v Speaker 1>Of course, if we go from ablo in the R group and we go to R-Ir, we we will still have Ablo.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:34.640
<v Speaker 1>We will change an O for an O.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:36.160
<v Speaker 1>So we don't do that.

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:38.260
<v Speaker 1>Ablo will also become able.

00:04:38.260 --> 00:04:44.260
<v Speaker 1>So again we have a situation where I jumps in with he, she, it and you formal.

00:04:44.260 --> 00:04:48.500
<v Speaker 1>So able can also be the mood tense for I

00:04:49.220 --> 00:04:52.020
<v Speaker 1>What is we speak?

00:04:54.020 --> 00:04:56.900
<v Speaker 1>And the mood tense of we speak

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:01.000
<v Speaker 1>Ablemos, good.

00:05:01.479 --> 00:05:07.560
<v Speaker 1>We are using the e, not that odd i that pops up with the eel verbs in the present, no?

00:05:07.560 --> 00:05:12.199
<v Speaker 1>Like vivimos, salimos, emos for the mood tense, able.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:15.040
<v Speaker 1>What was to eat?

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:15.920
<v Speaker 2>Comer.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:17.120
<v Speaker 1>Comer.

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:19.200
<v Speaker 1>I eat.

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:19.920
<v Speaker 2>Como.

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:20.480
<v Speaker 1>Como.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:22.720
<v Speaker 1>But the mood tense version would be

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:25.840
<v Speaker 1>Good, comma.

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:29.520
<v Speaker 1>And what else can comma mean then?

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:32.400
<v Speaker 1>He she it version of the mood tense.

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:33.680
<v Speaker 1>Good and new formal.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:34.480
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:05:34.480 --> 00:05:37.920
<v Speaker 1>Theyid normal uh tense, present tense.

00:05:39.140 --> 00:05:40.020
<v Speaker 2>Common.

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:44.740
<v Speaker 1>Common and the mood tense common.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:45.460
<v Speaker 1>Common.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:46.100
<v Speaker 1>Good

00:05:46.139 --> 00:05:53.580
<v Speaker 1>So it's going to be great to practice this mood tense because of course you you have to first think what the verb should be and then you switch it.

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.060
<v Speaker 1>So we're going to have a nice practice.

00:05:55.740 --> 00:06:02.700
<v Speaker 1>mentally in our mental exercises of the tenses that we already learned whilst we are building the mood tense.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:08.620
<v Speaker 1>So the use of the mood tense we can divide between obligatory and optional

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:16.000
<v Speaker 1>There are some situations in which we absolutely must use the mood tense, otherwise it will be considered an error.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:16.479
<v Speaker 1>It will

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:19.900
<v Speaker 1>It will sound incorrect and distract from what we're saying.

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:24.300
<v Speaker 1>And then there are cases where the use of the mood tense is optional.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:25.340
<v Speaker 1>You can use it

00:06:25.360 --> 00:06:33.280
<v Speaker 1>To give a different meaning or a different flavor or a different feeling, which is the much more exciting area where it's optional

00:06:33.240 --> 00:06:42.120
<v Speaker 1>But the obligatory uses will allow us a very important exposure to the feeling of the mood tense

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:44.780
<v Speaker 1>So now we're going to look at some examples.

00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:51.099
<v Speaker 1>In English when you say I want you to wait, I want you to wait

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:55.520
<v Speaker 1>This is quite a peculiar structure in English.

00:06:55.520 --> 00:07:00.000
<v Speaker 1>And it's not really translated in this way in many other languages.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.520
<v Speaker 1>I want you to wait.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:11.320
<v Speaker 1>In most other Romance languages at least it's translated as I want that you wait.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:16.440
<v Speaker 1>This is how we would say it in French or Portuguese or Italian.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:20.960
<v Speaker 1>So I want you to wait is I want that you wait.

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:28.080
<v Speaker 1>Now this you wait is going to be in the mood tense when we are expressing what we want.

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:31.100
<v Speaker 1>In this way, we will use the mood tense.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:37.340
<v Speaker 1>We are putting our subjectivity onto the world when we say, I want that.

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:41.840
<v Speaker 1>And following this, that, we will use the mood tense.

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:44.400
<v Speaker 1>So how would you say I want you to wait?

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:47.280
<v Speaker 1>I want that you wait informally

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:52.199
<v Speaker 2>So I want remains the same and it's quiero.

00:07:52.199 --> 00:07:57.000
<v Speaker 2>That is key and then you wait.

00:07:57.020 --> 00:07:59.420
<v Speaker 2>becomes espere.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:00.860
<v Speaker 2>I'm sorry, esperes.

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:01.180
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:02.780
<v Speaker 1>Altogether I want that you wait.

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:05.020
<v Speaker 2>Quiero che esperes.

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:05.500
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:11.960
<v Speaker 1>So if you say Quiro que esperas, here it would be considered an error.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:16.040
<v Speaker 1>This is an obligatory use of the subjunctive of the mood tense.

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:17.560
<v Speaker 1>Quiro que esperes.

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:21.960
<v Speaker 1>I want you to wait for him or I want you to wait for it.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:24.960
<v Speaker 2>Quiero que lo esperes.

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:25.600
<v Speaker 1>Good.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:27.520
<v Speaker 1>Quiero que lo esperes.

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.760
<v Speaker 1>I want you to wait for it all for him.

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:30.880
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.800
<v Speaker 1>Do you want me to wait?

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.120
<v Speaker 1>So first let's find the in-between sentence.

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:38.000
<v Speaker 1>Give it to me in English how we will say in Spanish.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.159
<v Speaker 1>Do you want me to wait?

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:44.099
<v Speaker 1>Do you want that I wait for you?

00:08:44.099 --> 00:08:45.620
<v Speaker 1>You made it more complicated.

00:08:45.620 --> 00:08:47.860
<v Speaker 1>It's just do you want that I wait?

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:48.180
<v Speaker 1>But

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:50.440
<v Speaker 1>Let's put it.

00:08:50.440 --> 00:08:53.880
<v Speaker 1>So do you want me to wait for you?

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:55.080
<v Speaker 1>Give me that one.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:56.680
<v Speaker 1>Do you want me to wait for you?

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:59.240
<v Speaker 1>And let's speak informally.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:03.360
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:05.760
<v Speaker 1>Quieres que te espere.

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.760
<v Speaker 1>And of course this could mean

00:09:08.120 --> 00:09:10.279
<v Speaker 1>Do you want me to wait for you?

00:09:10.279 --> 00:09:12.120
<v Speaker 1>Do you want him to wait for you?

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:14.839
<v Speaker 1>Do you want her to wait for you?

00:09:14.839 --> 00:09:19.240
<v Speaker 1>So if we wanted to clarify I, how would we do that?

00:09:19.240 --> 00:09:22.760
<v Speaker 1>Do you want me to wait for you?

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:27.160
<v Speaker 1>Very good.

